:::summary
John Milton (1608–1674) was the greatest English poet after Shakespeare — a classically trained Puritan scholar whose epic *Paradise Lost* (1667) retells the story of the Fall of Man with such theological depth, psychological insight, and sublime poetic power that it stands as the supreme achievement of English letters and one of the most important works of Christian literature ever written.
:::

